<Content>I admit I am not what you would call technically sophisticated. After suffering through the limitations of portable CD players, my main criteria when looking for a player was being able to put a lot of music in one space while having good, clean and crisp sound.  Initially, I got my feet wet by buying a 512 MB flash player and eventually wanted to include more songs on the player. That led me to larger players. But which one to buy ... the dominant Ipod or another player which gets less attention? I have an older version of Windows which quickly ruled out the Ipod. So I turned to Creative Zen which was not only compatible technically but financially.  But I had huge concerns as I read reviews complaining about the player freezing and breaking. So it was with trepidation that I bought the Creative Zen Micro.   Hopefully, I don't jinx myself but 8 months later, I can report I am enjoying my player and its capabilities. When I first received the player, I was ready to throw it across the room (the $200 I paid stopped me from doing that) because I was so frustrated over not being able to work the touchpad. It took a few days but once I took a deep breath and managed to adjust the sensitivity levels, things were fine. The FM stations come in clear as well and the battery which I can remove and replace myself (an advantage over the Ipod) lasts a reasonable period of time without recharging.  Because the player came with few instructions, another frustration I had was not being able to figure out how to make playlists and other functions. I fixed that problem by going to Creative's website and finding a 65 page set of instructions there. For those who are still trying to figure out their player, I recommend downloading the instructions. It makes life and dealing with the player much easier.  
