<Review ID>5281407
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Green
<Title>Works for me
<Date>Thu Nov 10 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>First of all, I was aware of the sensitive touch pad and of the headphone jack problem before I bought this.    When I first got it I opened the insturction manual and did what it said.  The manual doesn't tell you how to use your player but only tells you how to charge it up, turn it on,  and install the software on your computer and that's it.  Using the player itself you'll have to play with it to figure it out.  The software that comes with this is good.  It comes with Windows media player 10 and its own organizer.  The organizer is actually powered by Windows media player and a couple of other programs.  You can use windows media player to rip, burn cds, and sync music to your device if you want to, but I like creatives organizer better.  Using the player itself is easy once you get the hang of it.  You slide your thumb up and down the touch pad to select the menu item(don't tap it or press it) then once your on the thing you want you then tap the touch pad to select it.  The first thing you'll want to do when you get it is practice doing this.  You might also want to change the touchpad sensitivity to low in system/player settings/touch pad.  Also when playing music you have to use the touch pad to turn up and down the volume.  There is no seperate wheel or buttons for the volume.  What I mean is once you press play and start playing the file, you use the same touch pad you use for navigating the menus for the volume.  Personally I don't mind this.  I haven't tried making a play list using the player itself yet so I can't comment on that.  It is easy however to make one on your computer and import it to your device.  As for audio quality it's just as good as any other MP3 player.  Nothing special but it's good.  It's not distroted or anything like that.  There is a little bit of squeeling in between tracks though.  As for problems my device did freeze up once and I had to remove the battery and stick it back in.  That fixed the problem and none of the data was lost.  I haven't run into the headphone jack problem yet and I hope I never do.  I've only had it for a little over a month though.  I'm being extra carefull making sure not to twist the headphone plug around in the jack and not removing it and putting it back in all the time.  The only other problem is that the touchpad is hard to use at first but you get used to it.  Pros: -Plays MP3 and WMA -Small about three inches tall, one and a half inches wide and less than a half inch deep -FM radio -comes with good software  Cons -unsure about headphone jack -froze up once  
<Overall>4

